Monica Perin


Houston Business Journal







 






Bizspace Spotlight
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Property Spotlight: Class A Office Space | Clear Lake                




See All Bizspace Properties



 
 











 Enlarge





                W.A. Parrish generating station in Ft. Bend County            








 



Despite the recent well-publicized success of environmental groups in getting eight proposed coal-fired power plants in Texas scrapped, coal, as a fuel, isn't going away any time soon.
That's significant for Houston, which is home to some significant players in the coal industry.













 Enlarge






                            W.A. Parrish generating station in Ft. Bend County                        










 


The battle between the "green" lobby and the market forces behind coal came to a head recently when New York-based Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and Fort Worth-based Texas Pacific Group announced they had agreed to acquire Dallas-based utility TXU Corp. for $45 billion.
In an unprecedented move, the private equity firms invited a couple of high-profile environmental groups to the negotiating table and, in return for their support of the acquisition, agreed to the environmentalists' demands to cancel eight of the 11 coal-fired power plants TXU planned to build in Texas.
The deal was hailed by environmentalists as a watershed that would make other energy companies and their investors "think twice" about investing in new coal plants.
But players in the coal industry take a different view.
The United States sits atop 27 percent of the world's reserves of coal. Ninety percent of the coal produced in the country is used to generate electricity.
"Half the U.S. electric grid today is powered by coal," says James Rollyson, a coal industry analyst in the Houston office of Raymond James Financial Inc. "It's still the cheapest fuel. We have a lot of it. We don't have to import it. And it can be used relatively cleanly, so why wouldn't you use it?"
The same can't be said of natural gas-fired power plants. Many of these were built during the last decade because natural gas was cheap and burns much more cleanly than coal. But the price of gas has risen significantly and supply has tightened.
"Because of ongoing supply issues, we will have to rely on LNG (liquefied natural gas, an imported commodity) and cost-effective gas," Rollyson says. "There will be more building (of gas-fired power capacity) but not as much as in the past."

But coal, it would seem, is on solid ground.
In a 2006 report, Kiplinger's Personal Finance called coal "the new black gold," noting that the stock price of U.S. coal producers has left major oil companies in the dust despite record oil and gas prices. ExxonMobil Corp.'s shares, for example, gained 37 percent between 2004 and 2006, while shares of St. Louis-based Peabody Energy Corp. -- the largest coal producer in the world -- quadrupled.
Peabody's coal alone fuels more than 10 percent of the nation's electricity.
Kiplinger's also singled out Houston-based Natural Resource Partners LP. Although not a coal producer, the company makes its money from royalties on coal produced from land it owns. Those royalties are passed along to investors as dividends. NRP's dividends have increased for 11 straight quarters. The company's units are currently trading at around $63.
Natural Resource Partners is headed by Corbin J. Robertson Jr., grandson of famed Texas oilman Hugh Roy Cullen. Robertson's father diversified the family's oil business into coal in 1969, and Robertson now owns more than 20 billion tons of coal in the U.S. -- more than anyone else except the government.





Another innovative Houston coal-related company is DKRW Energy LLC.
As a fuel, coal's main drawback is that it produces large quantities of harmful pollutants like sulfur, mercury and carbon dioxide -- the greenhouse gas responsible for global warming.
But technologies are available that can clean up those undesirable side effects, and DKRW is applying some that have been around for some time to develop a coal-to-liquids plant in Wyoming.
The coal will come from a mine owned and operated by Arch Coal Inc. of St. Louis, the nation's second-largest producer. At the plant, DKRW will use coal-gasification technology developed by General Electric Co. to produce synthetic gas. Virtually all sulfur and carbon dioxide will be removed.
The synthetic gas will then be liquefied using another technology known as the Fischer-Tropsch process. Further refining will produce ultra-low-sulfur diesel fuel, all of which DKRW will sell to Sinclair Oil Corp. under a recently signed contract.
According to Stephen Leer, chief executive officer of Arch Coal, converting coal into liquid fuel or natural gas is economical as long as the price of oil is above $40 a barrel.
A related technology that also has been around for several decades and is now gaining prominence is known as the integrated gasification combined cycle. An IGCC plant uses synthetic gas produced in a coal gasification process as fuel for a combustion turbine. Heat recovered from the turbine exhaust and gasification process produces steam that boosts plant output and efficiency.
But most importantly, IGCC plants are conducive to efficiently removing or reducing emissions such as carbon dioxide.
Four IGCC power plant projects have been announced in Texas. Two IGCC demonstration plants will be built by TXU. Size, cost and location haven't been determined. Another will be built by Hunton Energy in Fort Bend County while Tondu Corp. is looking for investors for one on the Corpus Christi Ship Channel. The Hunton and Tondu plants won't burn coal, but coke, a waste product produced by petroleum refineries.
In another IGCC initiative, Houston-based oil major ConocoPhillips is involved in a project to develop standardized design specifications for building IGCC plants, a blueprint that is expected to reduce both the cost and time required to develop such facilities. The "CoalFleet for Tomorrow" project is headed by the Electric Power Research Institute, a trade group that is trying to promote advanced coal power generation technology.
"Coal-to-gas and coal-to-liquids plants represent a significant avenue for long-term industry growth," Peabody Energy CEO Gregory H. Boyce said in December as he announced a 45 percent increase in the company's earnings.
"These technologies are receiving growing bipartisan U.S. support," he said, pointing to bills such as the Coal-to-Liquids Fuel Promotion Act of 2006 introduced by Sen. Barack Obama, D-Ill., and Sen. Jim Bunning, R-Ky.
'Aggressive' target
The U.S. Department of Energy supports these technologies and has set as a goal the development of 90 gigawatts of IGCC power generation by 2025.
But Michelle Foss, head of the Center for Energy Economics of The University of Texas, thinks the DOE is "too aggressive" in its coal outlook.
"When it comes to utilizing coal, a lot of things are involved, and it all has to work together," says Foss who, earlier in her career, worked with the coal industry.




 


As for IGCC plants, "No one really knows what one would cost commercially because, in spite of all the talk, no one has really put any money on the table yet," she says, adding that "no one has figured out what to do about the mercury emissions."
Nevertheless, Foss isn't betting against the coal industry, which she says has always been "pretty successful in obtaining and preserving its support in the government."
Environmental groups, on the other hand, do not have a united front on the issue of coal. Some groups are willing to consider the use of coal with low emissions while others are anti-coal under any circumstances.
But, like the coal industry itself, environmental concerns aren't likely to go away.
"It's obvious that carbon dioxide will be the next emission to be regulated" in the U.S., says industry analyst Rollyson.
Even so, he says, "The economic picture indicates that coal will work to fill the gap as a utility fuel for the next 20 to 30 years. And it can be turned into clean liquid fuels, too, which are the equivalent of natural gas and are competitive at today's gas prices. This will drive the demand for coal.
"Coal is the fuel of choice going forward."
U.S. coal facts
? The United States has the largest coal reserves in the world -- more than 27 percent of the world's known supply. ? Ninety percent of coal produced is used in electricity generation.? Coal fuels more than 50 percent of all electricity generated, with nuclear power accounting for 20 percent and natural gas for 18 percent.? There are 275 billion tons of recoverable coal reserves, enough to last 250 years. Natural gas reserves are projected to last 10 years.? Annual demand for coal is 300 million tons.? In 2005, a record 1.13 billion tons of coal was produced.? Projection: 87 gigawatts of new coal-fueled generation facilities will be constructed by 2025.Sources: U.S. Energy Information Administration, American Coal Council
Major holders of U.S. coal reserves 
(in billion tons)1. U.S. government -- 902. Great Northern Properties LP, Houston -- 203. Peabody Energy Corp., St. Louis, Mo. -- 9.34. Consol Energy Inc., Pittsburgh, Pa. -- 4.55. Arch Coal Inc., St. Louis, Mo. -- 3.76. North American Coal Corp., Dallas -- 2.47. Massey Energy Co., Richmond, Va. -- 2.29. Natural Resource Partners LP, Houston -- 1.815. TXU Mining Co., Dallas -- 0.6Source: Montana Coal Council, 2004 data
Top U.S. coal producers
1. Peabody Coal Co. -- 18%2. Rio Tinto Energy America Inc. -- 11% (an affiliate of U.K.- and Australia-based Rio Tinto Energy Group)3. Arch Coal -- 10.4%4. Consol Energy -- 5.8%5. Foundation Coal Corp. -- 5.7%6. Massey Coal Co. -- 3.7%7. North American Coal Corp. -- 2.7%9. TXU Corp. -- 2%Source: Energy Information Administration, 2005 data
Some coal industry players in Houston:
Traders: BP Energy Co. Coal & Emissions TradingDynegy Coal Trading & Transportation LLCKoch Carbon LLCStorage and transportation: Kinder Morgan Bulk Terminals Inc., a subsidiary of Houston-based Kinder Morgan Energy Partners LP.Providers of services to the coal industry: Mineral Resource Technologies, The Woodlands -- develops new applications and products from coal combustion; also operates transportation and product distribution system.SolArc Inc. -- develops risk management software for energy commodities, including coal.Producers: Natural Resource Partners LPMedicine Bow Fuel & Power LLC, a subsidiary of DKRW Advanced Fuels LLC
Electricity production cost (per megawatt hour)
Without CO2 capture: Old-style pulverized coal plant: $58IGCC plant: $63Combined-cycle natural gas: $90With CO2 capture: Coal: $94IGCC: $87Natural gas: $137Source: James Rollyson, Raymond James Financial

